  urldate = {2023-02-10},
  abstract = {The single breath carbon monoxide diffusing capacity (DLCO sb), also called the transfer factor (TLCO), was introduced by Marie and August Krogh in two papers (Krogh and Krogh, Skand. Arch. Physiol. 23, 236 {\'A}/247, 1909; Krogh, J. Physiol., Lond. 49, 271 {\'A}/296, 1915). Physiologically, their measurements showed that sufficient oxygen (by extrapolation from CO) diffused passively from gas to blood without the need to postulate oxygen secretion, a popular theory at the time. Their DLCO sb technique was neglected until the advent of the infra-red CO meter in the 1950s. Ogilvie et al., J. Clin. Invest., 1957, 36, 1 {\'A}/17 published a standardized technique for a `modified Krogh' single breath DLCO, which eventually became the method of choice in pulmonary function laboratories. The Roughton {\'A}/Forster equation (J. Appl. Physiol., 1957 11, 290 {\'A}/302) was an important step conceptually; it partitioned alveolar {\'A}/capillary diffusion of oxygen (O2) and carbon monoxide (CO) into a membrane component (DM) and a red cell component (u {\texttimes}/ Vc) where u is the DLCO (or DLO2) per ml of blood (measured in vitro), and Vc is the pulmonary capillary volume. This equation was based on the kinetics of O2 and CO with haemoglobin (Hb) in solution and with whole blood Hartridge and Roughton, Nature 1923, 111, 325 {\'A}/326; Proc. R. Soc. Lond. Ser. A 1923, 104, 376 {\'A}/394; (Proc. R. Soc. Lond. Ser. B 1923, 94, 336 {\'A}/367; Proc. R. Soc. Lond. Ser. A, 1923, 104, 395 {\'A}/430; J. Physiol., Lond. 1927, 62, 232 {\'A}/242; Roughton, Proc. R. Soc. Lond. Ser. B 1932, 111, 1 {\'A}/36) and on the relationship between alveolar PO2 and 1/DLCO. Subsequently, the relationship between DLO2 (Lilienthal et al., Am. J. Physiol. 147, 199 {\'A}/216, 1946) and DLCO was defined. More recently, the measurement of the nitric oxide diffusing capacity (DLNO) has been introduced. For DLO2 and DLNO the membrane component (as 1/DM) is an important part of the overall diffusion (transfer) resistance. For the DLCO, 1/u {\texttimes}/ Vc probably plays the greater role as the rate limiting step. A crucial question, the effect of unstirred plasma layers on the `true' value of uCO in vivo, has not been resolved, but this does not detract from the clinical role of the DLCO sb (TLCO) as an essential test of lung function.},
  langid = {english},
  file = {/Users/tgjcnt/Zotero/storage/C3M7S5WY/Hughes e Bates - 2003 - Historical review the carbon monoxide diffusing c.pdf}
}

